Good idea Beth, but now it's time for my question.

22
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.000
The sense of smell is incredibly powerful, but not everyone has it.

23
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:29.000
A small amount of the population is an osmic,

24
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.000
meaning they can't smell.

25
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:35.000
So, according to research at the University of Reading,

26
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
what percentage of people have no sense of smell

27
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:47.000
is it a 2% b5% or c7%?

28
00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
Oh, I'm going to say b5%.

29
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:57.000
Well, we'll find out the correct answer later in the program.

30
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Have you ever come back home from holiday and noticed a strange smell in your house?

31
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.000
If you have, don't worry, it's not bad.

32
00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
In fact, there's a scientific reason for it, as science writer,

33
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
Tristan Arton, explained to BBC World Service program

34
00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
unexpected elements.

35
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:23.000
One thing I've been thinking about is that every house or home has a smell to it.

36
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
You might really notice this in your own home when you come back from a long trip,

37
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:32.000
and you step to your front door and things smell a little weird.

38
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:38.000
While there's a good chance your house might smell strange because it's been closed up for a few weeks,

39
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
there's also a chance you might be smelling your home as it usually smells,

40
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.000
but you just don't notice it when you're there.

41
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:50.000
Tristan says that when you return home after being away,

42
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.000
there's a good chance your house smells weird,

43
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.000
an adjective meaning strange or unusual.

44
00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
If you say there's a good chance that something will happen,

45
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
you mean there's a high likelihood or probability of it.

46
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.000
The truth is that every home has a smell,

47
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
although we're so used to it, we usually don't notice.

48
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:16.000
When we breathe in, receptor cells in the nose detect molecules in the air

49
00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.000
and send them to old factory organs in the brain.

50
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:22.000
These analyze the smells for danger.

51
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
The reason you can't smell your own home is that it isn't a threat to you.

52
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Here's Science Writer, Tristan Arton again, explaining more to BBC World Service program

53
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
unexpected elements.

54
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Well, by filtering out common non-threatening smells,

55
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.000
it makes it easier to detect things out of the ordinary.

56
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:44.000
That might be dangerous.

57
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
So for example, if you forget about your toast and it starts to burn,

58
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
you can typically smell that quickly because it's a change to the environment that you're in,

59
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:58.000
then the other parts of your brain kick in to understand the smell of smoke as a potential harm or threat.

60
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.000
But even if we can't smell our own homes,

61
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:06.000
the scent of them still matters because it's entangled with our recognition of comfort and security.

62
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:13.000
By filtering out familiar smells, our brains are able to detect other smells which are out of the ordinary,

63
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.000
unusual or uncommon, and which may be dangerous.

64
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:23.000
To filter something out means to remove or separate something unwanted from something else.

65
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:29.000
For example, filtering out the smell of home means we notice the smell of burning toast

66
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.000
or other smells are letting us to possible danger.

67
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Even though we don't usually notice the scent, the particular smell of our home,

68
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.000
it still has an effect on the brain's limbic system, which handles memory and emotion.

69
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
This explains why smell has such a strong effect on our feelings,

70
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
and why we feel comfortable and safe at home.

71
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
Right, Phil, isn't it time to reveal the answer to your question?

72
00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Yes, it is.

73
00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Why ask you what percentage of the population is an osmic?

74
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
That means they can't smell.

75
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:08.000
And the answer is B5%, which is what you said, I think.

76
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:09.000
It is, yeah.

77
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Well done.

78
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program, starting with an osmic,

79
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
meaning having no sense or a limited sense of smell.

80
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
The adjective weird means strange odd or bizarre.

81
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:30.000
When someone says there's a good chance something will happen, they mean it's quite likely to happen.

82
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:36.000
The phrase out of the ordinary means unusual, uncommon or exceptional.

83
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:42.000
If you filter something out, you remove or separate something unwanted from substance.

84
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:48.000
And finally, a scent is a distinctive smell, often a pleasant one,

85
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:51.000
that it can also mean the smell made by an animal.

